  "_notes": [
    "Lexical lists are a FLOOR, not proof. Banned-word lists age: the PubMed study (arXiv 2406.07016) measured a ~25x jump in 'delves' in 2024 abstracts, and writers have since learned to avoid it. A hit raises suspicion; it never proves AI authorship, and a clean lexical pass never proves human authorship.",
    "Seeded from the PubMed excess-vocabulary study (arXiv 2406.07016: 280 excess style words, ~66% verbs, ~18% adjectives) plus curated practitioner lists. Edit freely; the linter reads only this file for word lists.",
    "Each lexical entry maps a tell to a suggested fix. null means 'usually cut the word entirely'. A value may also be an object {\"suggestion\": \"...\"} for forward-compatibility.",
    "Rotate stale tells over time: 'delve' spiked in 2024 then faded as writers learned to avoid it. Treat lexical hits as a floor and refresh this list as the model generation changes.",
    "The em-dash is treated as a strong tell, not a moderate one: em_dash_per_1k_words is low (2.0) and category_weights.em_dash is high (2.0). Replace nearly all em-dashes outside the creative register; creative already mutes em_dash + dash_style. The --fix autofixer rewrites em-dashes (and ASCII '--', spaced hyphens, non-numeric en-dashes) to commas and strips decorative emoji, except in creative (dashes + emoji kept) and casual (emoji kept)."
  ],
